# Three petty crimes in `src/petty.ts`

The crimes scan flagged exactly three findings on this file — one per function. Here's each, what an agent could break, and the refactor that earns the points.

---

## 1. `describeCheckout` — Option Bag Junk Drawer (`crime_00030`)

**Today (lines 10–19)**
```ts
interface CheckoutOptions {
  plan: string; role: string; region: string;
  currency: string; status: string; retry: boolean;
}
export function describeCheckout(options: CheckoutOptions) {
  return [options.plan, options.role, options.region,
          options.currency, options.status, String(options.retry)].join(":");
}
```

**Why it's an agent trap.** Five of the six fields are bare `string` — `plan`, `role`, `region`, `currency`, `status` are interchangeable to the compiler. An agent adding a new caller can pass `role` where `plan` is expected and every test passes. The `CheckoutOptions` name also implies a config-style grab bag, so an agent extending this function is likely to *add* a seventh field rather than question whether the existing six belong together. The crimes evidence ("6 distinct property reads") is the smoking gun — this isn't an options bag, it's six positional arguments wearing a trench coat.

**Refactor.** Replace the bag with a named, branded shape that reflects what `describeCheckout` actually does — produce a stable composite key:

```ts
type CheckoutKey = {
  plan: PlanId;       // branded string types
  role: Role;
  region: RegionCode;
  currency: CurrencyCode;
  status: CheckoutStatus;
  retry: boolean;
};
export function describeCheckout(key: CheckoutKey): string {
  return `${key.plan}:${key.role}:${key.region}:${key.currency}:${key.status}:${key.retry}`;
}
```

Branded types stop the role/plan swap; the rename (`options` → `key`) tells the next agent this isn't a place to dump new config.

---

## 2. `resolvePaymentResult` — Return Shape Roulette (`crime_00031`)

**Today (lines 21–32)**
```ts
if (input.error)    return { ok: false, code: input.code, message: input.message };
if (input.redirect) return { url: input.url, permanent: false };
return                     { ok: true, value: input.value, cached: false };
```

**Why it's an agent trap.** Three return shapes, **0% key overlap** between two of them (per the evidence). TypeScript infers the return type as a union, so callers either destructure unsafely or write `'ok' in result` probes. An agent adding a fourth branch (`{ pending: true, etag: '…' }`) won't see a compile error and won't realise existing callers don't handle it. The function name implies a single normalised result; the implementation says "good luck."

**Refactor.** Introduce a discriminated union so the compiler forces every caller (and every future agent) to handle each variant explicitly:

```ts
type PaymentResult =
  | { kind: "error";    code: string; message: string }
  | { kind: "redirect"; url: string;  permanent: boolean }
  | { kind: "success";  value: string; cached: boolean };

export function resolvePaymentResult(input: PaymentInput): PaymentResult {
  if (input.error)    return { kind: "error",    code: input.code!,    message: input.message! };
  if (input.redirect) return { kind: "redirect", url:  input.url!,     permanent: false };
  return                     { kind: "success",  value: input.value!,  cached: false };
}
```

The `kind` tag turns an agent's "add a fourth branch" mistake into a TypeScript error at every call site. Bonus: the input type stops being a six-field optional bag too — split it the same way if you have the budget.

---

## 3. `canRunBilling` — Negative Flag Maze (`crime_00032`)

**Today (lines 34–37)**
```ts
export function canRunBilling(disableBilling: boolean, skipRetry: boolean) {
  if (!disableBilling && !skipRetry) return true;
  return false;
}
```

**Why it's an agent trap.** Two negative flags (`disableBilling`, `skipRetry`) AND-ed under a `!`. Reading this requires inverting both operands in your head. The related finding `crime_00029` flags the same names as unprefixed booleans — together they mean an agent adding a third condition (say, `skipFraudCheck`) has to decide whether to keep the De Morgan pattern or break it, and either choice produces a subtly wrong predicate. Forty percent of the bug surface for a billing gate is in two words.

**Refactor.** Flip to positive flags at the boundary and name the predicate:

```ts
export function canRunBilling(billingEnabled: boolean, retryEnabled: boolean): boolean {
  return billingEnabled && retryEnabled;
}
```

If the call sites genuinely need to pass "disable" semantics (e.g. a feature-flag system), invert once at the call site, not inside the predicate. The function body now reads exactly as its name: billing runs when both are enabled. Extending it to a third flag is now safe — the next agent adds `&& fraudChecksEnabled` instead of negotiating a triple negative.

---

**Common thread.** All three are low-severity individually (the scan reports `agent_risk: 0.40` on each), but they cluster in a 38-line file — which is the point of `crimes context`. An agent loading just this file sees three different "I'll guess the contract" failure modes side by side. Naming the shapes (`CheckoutKey`, `PaymentResult`) and flipping the flags removes the guesswork before the next edit lands.
